Q3.  How many ways to handle Exception in java ?
there are many ways to handle exceptions :
1️⃣ try – catch :
- Jo v piece of code lgta hai ki wo exception de skta hai usko try block ke ander likhte hai.
- hr ek try ke sath atleast ek catch block likhna pdega . wo catch ho ya finaly but finaly exception ko suppress nhi krega but clean-up kr dega.
- catch block exception ko safely handle kar leta hai. jisse Program terminate nahi hota. or aage ki line execute hoti hai.
- Multiple catch blocks : Ek try ke saath multiple catch blocks likh sakte hain.
       - Child / specific exception pehle
       - Parent exception baad me
- Multi-Catch Block (| operator) : Jab multiple exceptions ke liye same handling logic ho, tab ek hi catch me | operator ka use karte hain.
        - Parent–child exception allowed nahi hoti.
        - Multi-catch me exception variable implicitly final hota hai :  catch (A | B e) {  e = new Exception(); // ❌ not allowed }
🔹 finally block :
- finally block exception aaye ya na aaye, hamesha execute hota hai.
              - Resource clean-up ke liye (file close, DB connection close, etc.)
              -  finally exception ko handle ya suppress nahi karta, sirf clean-up ka kaam karta hai.
              - even catch block me return keyword likha hoga still finally block chlega.
🔹 Try-with-resources :
- Try-with-resources Java 7 me introduce hua tha..
- Ye finally block ka alternative mana jata hai resource closing ke case me.(General finally ka full replacement nahi hai — sirf resources close karne ke liye).
- Resources try() ke parentheses ke andar declare kiye jaate hain. Jaise hi try block se bahar aate hain:
           - chahe exception aaye ya na aaye, resource automatically close ho jata hai.
- Jo bhi resource try-with-resources me use hota hai: AutoCloseable interface implement karta hai, JVM automatically close() method call karti hai.
